subSubSection.paragraph:
Dorsocaudally the common genital atrium receives the female duct (described as “common duct” by
Meixner 1915
). This female duct is a relatively long, broad tube lined with the same epithelium as the common genital atrium and provided with strongly-developed circular muscles. Proximally it receives the oviduct, the vitelloducts, the seminal receptacle and the eosinophilic secretion of the female glands. The single ovary is relatively large in the animals from Laguna de Santa Olalla and smaller in the animals from the other localities. In live animals it was observed on the right side of the body, next to the centrally-located copulatory organ. The oviduct is broad and lined with a thin epithelium. The large, spherical seminal receptacle is filled with sperm and has a relatively high, nucleated epithelium. A short stalk, surrounded by a strong sphincter of several circular muscles, connects the seminal receptacle with the female duct.
